<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="126" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="126">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="126">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linné" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Monochamus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Monochamus sutor" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sutor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="126">Monochamus sutor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a boreal montane species that is widely distributed in Europe; in Asia, it is known from Georgia, Russia, Kazakhstan, and Mongolia. It is also an invasive species in North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Danilevsky, ML" journalOrPublisher="HSC, Moscow" pageId="23" pageNumber="130" publicationUrl="http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" refId="B11" refString="Danilevsky, ML, 2017a. Catalogue of Palaearctic Cerambycoidea. [Updated: 15.02.2017] http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" title="Catalogue of Palaearctic Cerambycoidea. [Updated: 15.02.2017]" url="http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" year="2017 a">Danilevsky 2017a</bibRefCitation>
). This species is ecologically associated with various conifer trees. Its life cycle lasts from one to three years. The imagines are active from June to mid-September (
<bibRefCitation author="Cherepanov, AI" journalOrPublisher="Oxonian Press, New Delhi" pageId="23" pageNumber="130" refId="B4" refString="Cherepanov, AI, 1990c. . Cerambycidae of northern Asia. Vol. 3, Lamiinae Part I. Oxonian Press, New Delhi" title=". Cerambycidae of northern Asia. Vol. 3, Lamiinae Part I." year="1990 c">Cherepanov 1990c</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kolk, A" journalOrPublisher="Multico, Warszawa" pageId="25" pageNumber="132" refId="B38" refString="Kolk, A, Starzyk, JR, 1996. Small white-marmorated longhorned beetle - Monochamus sutor L., Atlas szkodliwych owadow lesnych. Multico, Warszawa" title="Small white-marmorated longhorned beetle - Monochamus sutor L., Atlas szkodliwych owadow lesnych." year="1996">Kolk and Starzyk 1996</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="126">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pic" baseAuthorityYear="1898" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Monochamus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Monochamus sutor subsp. longulus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="sutor" subSpecies="longulus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="126">Monochamus sutor longulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a more eastern range compared to the nominative subspecies, and is distributed from East Siberia through northern Mongolia, China and North Korea to the Far East and Japan. It differs from the nominative form 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="126">inter alia</emphasis>
in its slightly more elongated elytra with glabrous and shining surface. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Wallin, H" journalOrPublisher="Norwegian Journal of Entomology" pageId="26" pageNumber="133" pagination="11 - 38" refId="B68" refString="Wallin, H, Schroeder, M, Kvamme, T, 2013. A review of the European species of Monochamus Dejean, 1821 (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) - with a description of the genitalia characters. Norwegian Journal of Entomology 60: 11 - 38" title="A review of the European species of Monochamus Dejean, 1821 (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) - with a description of the genitalia characters." volume="60" year="2013">Wallin et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
, there is no difference in the male genitalia characters between the examined specimens of those two subspecies.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="126">
In Mongolia, this taxon was probably incorrectly identified in certain works (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Heyrovsky, L" journalOrPublisher="Reichenbachia" pageId="24" pageNumber="131" pagination="39 - 46" refId="B22" refString="Heyrovsky, L, 1965. Ergebnisse der zoologischen Forschungen von Dr. Z. Kaszab in der Mongolei, 47. Cerambycidae II (Coleoptera). Reichenbachia 7 (3): 39 - 46" title="Ergebnisse der zoologischen Forschungen von Dr. Z. Kaszab in der Mongolei, 47. Cerambycidae II (Coleoptera)." volume="7" year="1965">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Heyrovský">Heyrovsky</normalizedToken>
1965
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/mmnz.19690450204" author="Heyrovsky, L" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum in Berlin" pageId="24" pageNumber="131" pagination="225 - 229" refId="B26" refString="Heyrovsky, L, 1969. Cerambycidae (Coleoptera) aus der Mongolei. Ergebnisse der Mongolisch-Deutschen Expeditionen seit 1962, Nr. 41. Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum in Berlin 45 (2): 225 - 229, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1002/mmnz.19690450204" title="Cerambycidae (Coleoptera) aus der Mongolei. Ergebnisse der Mongolisch-Deutschen Expeditionen seit 1962, Nr. 41." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/mmnz.19690450204" volume="45" year="1969">1969</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Heyrovsky, L" journalOrPublisher="Staatliches Museum fuer Tierkunde in Dresden" pageId="24" pageNumber="131" pagination="119 - 125" refId="B28" refString="Heyrovsky, L, 1973a. Ergebnisse der zoologischen Forschungen von Dr. Kaszab in der Mongolei, 253. Cerambycidae VI (Coleoptera). Faunistische Abhandlungen. Staatliches Museum fuer Tierkunde in Dresden 4 (14): 119 - 125" title="Ergebnisse der zoologischen Forschungen von Dr. Kaszab in der Mongolei, 253. Cerambycidae VI (Coleoptera). Faunistische Abhandlungen." volume="4" year="1973 a">1973a</bibRefCitation>
) and it was recorded as 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Monochamus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Monochamus sutor subsp. var. var. pellio" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="variety" species="sutor" subSpecies="var." variety="pellio">Monochamus sutor var. pellio</taxonomicName>
(Germar, 1818), which is currently recognized as a synonym of the nominative subspecies.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="126">
One female was reared from a branch of a fallen tree of 
<taxonomicName class="Coniferopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Larix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Larix sibirica" order="Pinales" pageId="19" pageNumber="126" phylum="Gymnospermae" rank="species" species="sibirica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="126">Larix sibirica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected in forest steppe habitat (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 7. Field photos of immature stages and habitats of typical Mongolian cerambycid species: A larches in forest steppe, the habitat of Lepturalia nigripes rufipennis B larva of L. nigripes in a birch stump C site in light taiga, the habitat of L. nigripes rufipennis and Agapanthia pilicornis pilicornis D site in forest steppe, the habitat of Clytus arietoides, Monochamus impluviatus impluviatus and M. sutor longulus E broken trunk of the birch in light taiga, the microhabitat of inter alia Xylotrechus hircus and Aegomorphus obscurior F birches in light taiga, the habitat of X. hircus, A. obscurior, Saperda scalaris hieroglyphica and Mesosa myops G larva of Xylotrechus pantherinus H larva of X. pantherinus deep in the wood of a standing willow trunk." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.739.23675.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/187660" pageId="19" pageNumber="126">7D</figureCitation>
). The same material was inhabited by larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reitter" authorityYear="1900" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Clytus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Clytus arietoides" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arietoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="126">Clytus arietoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Monochamus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Monochamus impluviatus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="impluviatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="126">Monochamus impluviatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
